      { "@type": "HowToStep", "position": 4, "name": "Select the next standard rating", "text": "Round up to the next standard MCB size: 6A, 10A, 16A, 20A, 25A, 32A, 40A, 50A, or 63A. Then select the correct curve type: B for resistive loads, C for motor loads." },
    ]
  },
  {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How do I choose the correct MCB rating?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Calculate load current (Watts ÷ 230V), apply a 1.25 safety margin, and round up to the next standard MCB rating: 6A, 10A, 16A, 20A, 25A, 32A, 40A, 50A, or 63A. For motor loads (AC, pump, fridge), use a Type C curve MCB. For lights and pure resistive loads, use Type B." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What MCB rating do I need for a 1.5 Ton AC?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A 1.5 Ton split AC draws about 6.5–8A continuously. With the 1.25 safety margin the design current is ~10A, but because AC compressors have a high inrush surge, a 16A Type C MCB on a dedicated circuit is the industry standard recommendation." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is the difference between a B curve and C curve MCB?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Type B MCBs have a magnetic trip threshold of 3–5× rated current and are used for resistive loads (lighting, heaters). Type C MCBs trip at 5–10× rated current and are designed for inductive/motor loads (ACs, pumps, refrigerators) that produce starting current surges." }},
