---

<KnowledgeHubLayout
  title="How to Choose the Right MCB Rating — The Definitive Guide"
  description="Master the 4-step formula for MCB sizing. Covers ampere calculation, B/C/D curve types, wire-gauge pairing, and worked examples for every circuit in your home — ACs, geysers, pumps, and main incomers."
  keywords="how to choose mcb rating, mcb size selection, b curve vs c curve mcb, wire gauge mcb pairing, circuit breaker sizing india, 16a mcb load capacity"
  breadcrumb={[
    { label: 'Home',          href: '/' },
    { label: 'Knowledge Hub', href: '/knowledge-hub' },
    { label: 'MCB Sizing',    href: '/knowledge-hub/mcb-sizing' },
    { label: 'How to Choose the Right MCB Rating' },
  ]}
  toc={toc}
  readingTime={9}
  datePublished="2026-06-19"
  dateModified="2026-06-20"
  schemaGraph={schemaGraph}
  relatedArticles={relatedArticles}
  clusterSlug="mcb-sizing"
  clusterTitle="MCB Sizing"
  showProgressBar={true}
  nextStep={{ clusterSlug: 'mcb-sizing', slug: 'why-does-my-mcb-keep-tripping', caption: 'Troubleshooting' }}
>

  <!-- ① QUICK ANSWER -->
  <QuickAnswerBox id="quick-answer" heading="The One Thing Most People Get Wrong">
    <p>
      Choosing an MCB is <em>not</em> just about amps. Most homeowners pick the right ampere rating
      and then install the wrong <strong>curve type</strong> — causing either nuisance trips every time
      the AC starts, or dangerously slow protection on a circuit that needs fast response.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Every MCB has <strong>two numbers</strong> that matter: the <strong>ampere rating</strong>
      (how much continuous current it allows) and the <strong>curve type</strong> (how fast it reacts
      to a sudden surge). Both must be correct. Here's the quick formula:
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed list-none">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <span class="font-mono font-bold text-accent flex-shrink-0">①</span>
        <span><strong>Design current</strong> = (Total Watts ÷ 230V) × 1.25</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <span class="font-mono font-bold text-accent flex-shrink-0">②</span>
        <span><strong>Round up</strong> to the next standard rating: 6 / 10 / 16 / 20 / 25 / 32 / 40 / 63A</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <span class="font-mono font-bold text-accent flex-shrink-0">③</span>
        <span><strong>Curve:</strong> Type B for lights & heaters — Type C for motors, ACs & pumps</span>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm">
      Example: 2,300W geyser → 2300 ÷ 230 = 10A → 10 × 1.25 = 12.5A → next size up = <strong>16A Type B</strong>
      (geysers are purely resistive, so Type B is correct here). Read on for the full explanation and every common circuit worked out.
    </p>
  </QuickAnswerBox>

  <p class="mt-6">Get MCB sizing right and you have invisible, reliable protection for decades. Get it wrong and you face either constant nuisance trips — or worse, a silent fire hazard hiding inside your walls.</p>

  <!-- ② WHAT AN MCB ACTUALLY PROTECTS -->
  <h2 id="why-mcb">What an MCB Actually Protects</h2>

  <p>An MCB protects your <strong>copper wiring</strong> — not your appliances. Exceed a wire's safe current rating and it heats up, its insulation melts, and a fire can start inside your wall — completely hidden until it breaks out.</p>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">MCB Rating vs. Outcome</p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 mt-2 list-none text-sm text-text-secondary">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-danger mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
        <span><strong>Rated too high:</strong> Wire overheats and may ignite before the MCB ever trips.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-success mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>
        <span><strong>Rated correctly:</strong> MCB trips before wire temperature reaches the danger point.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
        <span><strong>Rated too low:</strong> Nuisance trips during normal use even though nothing is wrong.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- ③ THE 4-STEP FORMULA -->
  <h2 id="step-by-step">The 4-Step Sizing Formula</h2>
  <p>
    This is the method used by professional electricians. It takes under 2 minutes once you know
    your appliance wattage.
  </p>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Sum the wattage of the circuit</strong>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Add up peak running wattages of every device that could run simultaneously. For a dedicated appliance (AC, geyser, pump), it's just that one device's wattage from its rating label. Label shows Amps? <code class="text-xs">Watts = Amps × 230</code></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Calculate the load current (Amps)</strong>
      <p class="font-mono text-sm bg-base border border-border rounded-lg px-4 py-2.5 mt-1 text-accent">Load Current (A) = Total Watts ÷ 230V</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Apply the 1.25 safety margin</strong>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Continuous loads (geysers, ACs, heaters) build heat inside the panel over time. Running at 80% of MCB capacity prevents thermal nuisance trips — so size the MCB for 125% of your calculated load.</p>
      <p class="font-mono text-sm bg-base border border-border rounded-lg px-4 py-2.5 mt-2 text-accent">Design Current (A) = Load Current × 1.25</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Select the next standard MCB rating</strong>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Round your design current <em>up</em> to the nearest standard size — never down. Then choose the curve type (next section). Both are printed on the breaker face, e.g. <code>C16</code> = Type C, 16A.</p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-3">
        {['6A', '10A', '16A', '20A', '25A', '32A', '40A', '50A', '63A'].map(r => (
          <span class="px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md text-xs font-mono font-semibold bg-accent/10 text-accent border border-accent/20">{r}</span>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ④ CURVE TYPES -->
  <h2 id="curve-types">B, C & D Curve Types — The Half of MCB Sizing Nobody Talks About</h2>

  <p>The ampere rating controls sustained-overload protection. The curve type controls how fast the breaker reacts to a sudden current spike. Getting the curve wrong is the #1 preventable mistake — motor inrush current (5–8× running amps) triggers a Type B breaker every time a motor starts, because the breaker cannot tell the difference between inrush and a short circuit.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Curve</th>
          <th>Magnetic Trip At</th>
          <th>Use For</th>
          <th class="text-danger">Do NOT Use For</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <span class="px-2.5 py-1 rounded font-mono font-bold text-sm text-accent" style="background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent), transparent 88%); border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent), transparent 70%);">Type B</span>
          </td>
          <td class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold">3–5× rated current</td>
          <td class="text-xs leading-relaxed">Lighting, heaters, resistive sockets, home office</td>
          <td class="text-xs text-danger leading-relaxed">ACs, pumps, refrigerators, washing machines</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <span class="px-2.5 py-1 rounded font-mono font-bold text-sm" style="color: #d97706; background: color-mix(in srgb, #f59e0b, transparent 88%); border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, #f59e0b, transparent 70%);">Type C</span>
          </td>
          <td class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold">5–10× rated current</td>
          <td class="text-xs leading-relaxed">ACs, water pumps, refrigerators, washing machines, motors</td>
          <td class="text-xs text-danger leading-relaxed">Pure lighting circuits (wasteful oversizing)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <span class="px-2.5 py-1 rounded font-mono font-bold text-sm text-danger" style="background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--danger), transparent 88%); border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--danger), transparent 70%);">Type D</span>
          </td>
          <td class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold">10–20× rated current</td>
          <td class="text-xs leading-relaxed">Very large motors, transformers, X-ray machines, welding equipment</td>
          <td class="text-xs text-danger leading-relaxed">Any domestic home circuit — D curves give inadequate protection for household wiring</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">Reading the label on your MCB</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
      The label on the front face of every MCB shows the curve letter followed immediately by the
      ampere rating. Examples:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-none text-sm text-text-secondary">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>
        <span><code class="text-sm font-mono font-bold">B16</code> — Type B curve, 16 Amps. Correct for a general lighting or socket circuit.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-accent mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>
        <span><code class="text-sm font-mono font-bold">C16</code> — Type C curve, 16 Amps. Correct for a 1.5 Ton AC or water pump circuit.</span>
      </li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-4 h-4 text-danger mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="18" y1="6" x2="6" y2="18"/><line x1="6" y1="6" x2="18" y2="18"/></svg>
        <span><code class="text-sm font-mono font-bold">B16 on an AC circuit</code> — Wrong curve type. Will trip every time the compressor starts, even though the wiring and appliance are both fine.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- ⑤ WIRE GAUGE PAIRING -->
  <h2 id="wire-pairing">MCB ↔ Wire Gauge Pairing — The Rule You Cannot Break</h2>

  <p>The MCB and its cable are a matched pair — the breaker's ampere rating must <strong>never exceed the cable's current-carrying capacity</strong>. If it does, the wire overheats before the breaker trips.</p>
  <p>This is why swapping a tripping 16A breaker for a 32A is so dangerous — the 2.5 mm² wire behind it was only designed for 18–20A.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Copper Wire Gauge</th>
          <th>Safe Current Capacity</th>
          <th>Maximum MCB Rating</th>
          <th>Typical Application</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>1.0 mm²</code></td>
          <td>10–12A</td>
          <td><strong>6A</strong></td>
          <td>Light fittings, very small loads</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>1.5 mm²</code></td>
          <td>13–15A</td>
          <td><strong>6A or 10A</strong></td>
          <td>Lighting circuits, small fan circuits</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>2.5 mm²</code></td>
          <td>18–20A</td>
          <td><strong>16A or 20A</strong></td>
          <td>General power sockets, ACs up to 1.5 Ton, small pumps</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>4 mm²</code></td>
          <td>25–27A</td>
          <td><strong>25A or 32A</strong></td>
          <td>Geysers, 2 Ton ACs, kitchen heavy circuits</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>6 mm²</code></td>
          <td>32–35A</td>
          <td><strong>32A or 40A</strong></td>
          <td>Sub-distribution board feeders</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>10 mm²</code></td>
          <td>44–50A</td>
          <td><strong>40A or 50A</strong></td>
          <td>Main incomer feeder for apartments</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>16 mm²</code></td>
          <td>60–65A</td>
          <td><strong>63A</strong></td>
          <td>Main incomer feeder for large homes / commercial</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-muted mt-4">
    <strong>Note:</strong> Current-carrying capacities above assume PVC-insulated copper conductors
    in conduit at 30°C ambient temperature. Values derate in high-temperature environments such
    as roof spaces — consult IS 1646 for full derating tables.
  </p>

  <!-- ⑥ REAL EXAMPLES -->
  <h2 id="real-examples">Real Sizing Examples — Every Common Home Circuit</h2>
  <p>
    Here is the 4-step formula applied to the three most common circuits in Indian homes — a lighting circuit, a dedicated AC circuit, and a geyser. These three cover the vast majority of residential sizing decisions.
  </p>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-3.5 h-3.5 text-accent inline-block mr-1.5 align-middle -translate-y-[1px]" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 1 0 18 0 9 9 0 0 0-18 0"/></svg>
      Example 1 — Lighting Circuit (LEDs + Fans)
    </p>
    <p>You have one circuit feeding 8 LED bulbs (9W each) and 3 ceiling fans (75W each).</p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Step 1 (Watts):</strong> (8 × 9) + (3 × 75) = 72 + 225 = <strong>297W</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 2 (Current):</strong> 297 ÷ 230 = <strong>1.29A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 3 (Safety):</strong> 1.29 × 1.25 = <strong>1.61A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 4 (Rating):</strong> Next standard size above 1.61A = <strong>6A Type B</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-text-muted">Wire: 1.5 mm² is adequate and standard for lighting circuits.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-3.5 h-3.5 text-accent inline-block mr-1.5 align-middle -translate-y-[1px]" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 1 0 18 0 9 9 0 0 0-18 0"/></svg>
      Example 2 — Dedicated 1.5 Ton AC Circuit
    </p>
    <p>A 1.5 Ton inverter split AC is rated at 1,600W continuous running power.</p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Step 1 (Watts):</strong> <strong>1,600W</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 2 (Current):</strong> 1,600 ÷ 230 = <strong>6.96A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 3 (Safety):</strong> 6.96 × 1.25 = <strong>8.70A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 4 (Rating):</strong> Next size above 8.70A = 10A. But AC compressors have inrush surges of 30–40A, so the industry standard is <strong>16A Type C</strong> on a dedicated circuit.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-text-muted">Wire: 2.5 mm² on a dedicated circuit. Do not share this circuit with other sockets.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-3.5 h-3.5 text-accent inline-block mr-1.5 align-middle -translate-y-[1px]" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 1 0 18 0 9 9 0 0 0-18 0"/></svg>
      Example 3 — Electric Geyser (Water Heater)
    </p>
    <p>A 2,000W instant geyser on a dedicated circuit.</p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Step 1 (Watts):</strong> <strong>2,000W</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 2 (Current):</strong> 2,000 ÷ 230 = <strong>8.70A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 3 (Safety):</strong> 8.70 × 1.25 = <strong>10.87A</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Step 4 (Rating):</strong> Next size above 10.87A = <strong>16A Type B</strong>. Geysers are purely resistive — no motor, no inrush surge — so Type B is correct and provides tighter, faster protection.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-text-muted">Wire: 2.5 mm² minimum. For 3,000W geysers, use 4 mm² cable and a 20A breaker.</p>
  </div>


