  <!-- ⑧ COMMON MISTAKES -->
  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common MCB Sizing Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <p>These are the five most expensive and most dangerous errors made during MCB selection:</p>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Upsizing the MCB without upgrading the wire</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">A tripping 16A breaker protects 2.5 mm² cable rated for 18–20A. Swapping for a 32A means the wire can overheat invisibly inside your wall before the breaker reacts. Fix the cause of tripping — never override the protection.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Using Type B on all motor circuits</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">Motor inrush current (5–8× running amps) triggers a Type B breaker's magnetic trip every time the motor starts — every single time. Specifying Type C for AC, pump, and fridge circuits costs nothing extra in planning.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Skipping the 1.25 safety margin on continuous loads</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">MCBs accumulate internal heat during sustained current — a geyser or heater running for hours can drift into trip territory even without a fault. The 1.25× margin (design to 80% capacity) gives the thermal headroom to stay stable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Running multiple heavy appliances on a single shared socket circuit</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">A general socket circuit is typically sized for 1,000–2,000W of light loads (TV, chargers, laptops). Geysers, ACs, washing machines, and water heaters each need their own dedicated circuit and MCB.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card mt-6">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
    <div>
      <strong class="text-text-primary block mb-1">Buying no-brand MCBs to save ₹50</strong>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-muted">No-brand MCBs can be mis-calibrated — failing to trip during a short circuit or tripping at the wrong current. A quality Schneider, Legrand, Siemens, ABB, or Hager MCB costs ₹120–250. Don't optimise a life-safety device for price.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ⑨ FAQS -->
  <KnowledgeHubCTA id="use-the-calculator" />

  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="kh-faq">
    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the standard MCB rating for a 1.5 Ton AC?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        The maths (1,600W ÷ 230V × 1.25 = 8.7A) points to 10A, but a 1.5T compressor's startup inrush can hit 30–40A for a fraction of a second — enough to trip even a 10A Type C. The industry standard is a <strong>16A Type C MCB on a dedicated 2.5 mm² circuit</strong>.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can one MCB protect two rooms?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        For lighting, yes — one 6A MCB can serve multiple rooms as long as total wattage stays below 1,380W. For power sockets, it is poor practice: a fault or overload in one room cuts power to both, and heavy-appliance loads frequently exceed the circuit rating.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can I use a 32A MCB to run my 1.5 HP water pump?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        No — a 32A MCB on a pump drawing only ~5A provides almost no meaningful protection. The wiring and pump windings can overheat well before the 32A breaker reacts. Use a <strong>16A Type C MCB</strong> on 2.5 mm² cable.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Does MCB rating affect my electricity bill?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        No — an MCB is a switch that draws zero power itself. Your meter measures energy consumed by appliances, not the capacity of your breakers. A 63A main breaker does not "use" more electricity than a 32A one.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the difference between a B curve and C curve MCB?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Type B trips at 3–5× rated current — fast and sensitive, ideal for lighting and resistive loads. Type C trips at 5–10× — giving motor inrush surges (ACs, pumps, fridges) room to pass without triggering a trip. Same ampere rating, very different behaviour during a surge event.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Why does my MCB trip when I turn on the geyser?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Three possibilities, in order of likelihood:
        <ol class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm list-decimal list-inside">
          <li><strong>Overloaded circuit:</strong> The geyser is sharing a circuit with other heavy loads (washing machine, heater). Run the geyser on a dedicated circuit.</li>
          <li><strong>Undersized MCB:</strong> A 3,000W geyser at 230V draws 13A. With the safety margin that's 16.25A — a 16A MCB will trip. You need a 20A MCB and 4 mm² cable.</li>
          <li><strong>Faulty heating element:</strong> An internal short in the element causes the breaker to trip instantly. The element must be tested and replaced by a plumber/electrician.</li>
        </ol>
        For a deeper diagnostic guide, see our article on
        <a href="/knowledge-hub/mcb-sizing/why-does-my-mcb-keep-tripping" class="text-accent hover:underline">why MCBs keep tripping</a>.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        How do I know what gauge wire is currently in my walls?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Check the distribution panel — cables to each MCB should have their size printed on the outer jacket (e.g., <code>2.5 mm² FR PVC</code>). A rule of thumb for Indian homes built after 1990: sockets use 2.5 mm², lighting uses 1.5 mm², sub-DB feeders use 6 mm² or larger. If unsure, have a licensed electrician inspect before changing any MCB ratings.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Is it safe to install an MCB myself without an electrician?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Working inside a distribution panel is risky — the incoming supply is always live even when all MCBs are off, and touching live busbars can be fatal. For a like-for-like MCB swap on an isolated circuit a careful DIYer can manage; for rewiring, adding circuits, or main board work, use a licensed electrician.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

